The course provides an overview of the research areas of sociology focusing on different social groups, their significance in the development of society and the impact on everyday life. The course introduces sociological theories of social differentiation and inequality. The course examines how gender, age, ethnicity, generation, social class, and sexual orientation are related to status, roles, equality and inequality in the modern information society and how they manifest in the context of social institutions (e.g., labour market, education, family, media). In addition, the opportunities to reduce the segregation and inequality of social groups will also be discussed.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aim is to provide an overview of the diversity of society focusing on different social groups and categories (including gender, ethnicity, age, sexual minorities) and their positions in society. The course introduces various sociological theories that explain the emergence of social differentiation and inequality.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  Student who has passed the course: 1. knows the basic concepts in sociology. 2. knows the essential theories on the diversification and differentiation of society. 3. understands the meaning and significance of social groups in modern society. 4. knows the role that different groups play in society and social institutions, as well as the role the different institutions play in creation of inequalities based on gender, ethnicity, age, etc. 5. is able to critically evaluate various forms of differentiation and inequality in the Estonian information society.
